  "prompt": "What is glycolysis?",
  "response": "Glycolysis is a metabolic pathway that breaks down glucose (a 6-carbon sugar) into two 3-carbon molecules of pyruvate. Here are key points about glycolysis:\n\n1. Location:\n- Occurs in the cytoplasm of cells\n- Happens in nearly all living organisms\n\n2. Process:\n- Involves 10 enzyme-catalyzed steps\n- Requires energy input initially (2 ATP molecules)\n- Produces energy in later steps (4 ATP molecules)\n- Net gain of 2 ATP molecules\n\n3. Overall chemical equation:\nGlucose + 2 NAD+ + 2 ADP + 2 Pi \u2192 2 Pyruvate + 2 NADH + 2 H+ + 2 ATP + 2 H2O\n\n4. Stages:\n- Energy investment phase (first 5 steps)\n- Energy generation phase (last 5 steps)\n\n5. Significance:\n- First step in cellular respiration\n- Occurs under aerobic and anaerobic conditions\n- Provides pyruvate for further energy production\n- Essential for generating ATP\n\n6. End product:\n- Pyruvate can enter:\n- Citric acid cycle (aerobic conditions)\n- Fermentation (anaerobic conditions)",
